The 'bee car' that avoids collisions
To advance the development of accident prevention technologies Nissan has taken inspiration, this time from nature, specifically bees.
The Japanese company has created a robot that, based on the flight of bees, avoids accidents.
This is the Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C, which is the first step in collision prevention technologies.
Engineers at Nissan Motor Co.'s Advanced Technical Center have developed this small robot in collaboration with the Center for Advanced Science and Technology Research at the prestigious University of Tokyo, Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, Director General of Public Relations for Technology and Brand Management Research and Development, the BR23C is presented as an expansion of Nissan's four-area Safety Shield.
This robot is intended to strengthen the collision prevention capability of the brand's vehicles.
During their flight, each bee creates its own oval-shaped personal space that closely resembles the Nissan Safety Shield.
But most importantly, the bee's composite eyes, capable of seeing at an angle of more than 300 degrees in all directions, allowing it to fly uninterrupted within its own personal space.
To recreate this visual function, engineers designed what they have called a laser range finder.
It detects obstacles up to two metres away within a 180-degree radius of the BR23C, calculates the distance to the object and sends a signal to an onboard microprocessor that immediately results in collision prevention.
"The moment it detects an obstacle, the little robot will mimic the movements of a bee and immediately change direction by turning its wheels at a right or higher angle to avoid collision.
The biggest difference with any existing system is that the evasion maneuver is totally instinctive.
Otherwise, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles", explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and chief engineer of this project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot be deflected up or down, nor diagonally; it can only move in two dimensions and in the direction that allows it to turn its wheels and not in infinite directions and ways like bees.
For this reason, Nissan has used a rotation function, in addition to acceleration and deceleration, to prevent the small robot from collisions.
"This device only needs to process information every few seconds, and act on that data.
It doesn't require saving information or intuitive logic from previous maneuvers, so it can work continuously with only a couple dozen KBs of memory.
This may come as a surprise, but we're not talking about memory gigs, not even mega gigs".
This is the first step in developing new instant collision prevention technologies, a technology Nissan predicts will be introduced into production cars within ten years.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries, which are lighter and last longer than the variety of lithium ions.
Another possible future application of this technology could be the integration of the unit with a GPS satellite navigation system to guide the driver to his destination avoiding roadblocks.
