Rafael Correa in Quito this Monday.
Refounding the republic around 21st century socialism.
This is the joint project of Venezuelan Hugo Chávez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Ecuadorian Rafael Correa.
This Sunday, following the example of his colleagues and friends, is the third to put a draft new constitution to the vote.
Mission accomplished: 64% of voters voted "yes" to the referendum, according to official results, which were 80% of the votes cast.
According to these results, the "no" got 28%, 7%, zero votes and 0.7% blank votes.
For the draft Constitution to be adopted, it had to get half the votes plus one.
On Sunday, two polls outside the polling stations and a count by a non-governmental organisation had announced a widespread victory for the "yes", estimating it at between 63% and 70%.
Rafael Correa had also claimed the victory of his draft Constitution on Sunday night.
"The Constitution triumphed overwhelmingly", he had assured, congratulating the Ecuadorians who head the government of Guayaquil, 280 kilometers southwest of Quito.
Thus, Rafael Correa has been congratulated by Chávez and Morales but also by his Chilean colleague Micaela Bachelet.
The elections, which will be held in full calm, according to the Organization of American States (OAS) observation mission, referred to a 444-point text consolidating the "new socialism" advocated by the president.
The draft Constitution implies increasing the power of the state over the economy, reserving to it the "development planning" of a country that lives essentially by extracting oil from foreign companies and by sending foreign currency to its emigrants.
Led by Correa, elected in 2006, the project also grants reinforced powers to the head of state, who can serve up to two consecutive four-year terms and have the possibility of dissolving the Assembly.
Correa has already announced that he will use this power and seek a new term in February 2009.
The Constitution also consolidates the principle of free health and education services that the president began to implement in this country of 13.9 million inhabitants, in which 50 percent of the population lives below the poverty line.
It also provides for the prohibition of the presence of foreign troops, which will end the agreement between Quito and Washington on the use of an Ecuadorian base as a starting point for US drug operations.
The 19 people kidnapped have been released in Chad
An Egyptian command launched an assault on the kidnappers of the eleven tourists and their eight companions captured ten days ago.
They're in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian companions kidnapped in the desert ten days ago arrived unharmed in the Egyptian capital after being released on Monday afternoon.
By morning, they had been released by Egyptian special forces in Chad.
All of them looked good when they arrived at 3:30 p.m. aboard a special plane at the Al Maza military base, adjacent to Cairo International Airport.
They were immediately transported by helicopters to the hospital in Maadi, a residential suburb of Cairo, for medical examination, so they have not been able to speak to the press.
"They are in good health" and "no ransom was paid" to the kidnappers, said Egypt's Tourism Minister Zoheir Garana at the airport.
On September 19, these hostages were taken by 35 unknown kidnappers while enjoying an outdoor safari in a deserted area at the foot of Mount Ouanat, on the borders of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, and have since moved from one node to another.
The group consisted of eleven tourists - five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian - and eight Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, a border guard and the director of the travel agency Aegyptous, which organises the safari.
An Egyptian security official said 30 special forces members, transported aboard two helicopters, had launched the assault during the night before dawn.
"A exchange of fire took place, and half of the kidnappers were killed, the others have fled", said the official, who kept his name.
According to him, 150 members of the Egyptian special forces of the "lightning" unit were sent to Sudan, where they were supported by German and Italian commandos.
The Italian Foreign Minister Franco Frattini mentioned in Belgrade the role played by the secret agents and members of the Italian special forces.
"We must recognize that we have achieved this result thanks to the professionalism and efficiency of our men of the secret services, the special forces", he said without going into detail.
He also denied the ransom payment.
The Sudanese army said it had intercepted a patrol vehicle on board which the kidnappers were on board, killing six, including the Chadian chief and detaining two.
He also claimed that they were linked to a Darfur rebel group, the Sudan-Unity Liberation Movement (SLA-U), a claim immediately denied by this group.
