The Dutch governments nationalize a part of Fortis Bank.
The Netherlands - the first in Europe - will help to nationalize the Belgian-Dutch bank Fortis, which is in trouble because of the impact of the mortgage crisis on the North American market: the three countries will support the financial and insurance institution, which also has operations in Hungary, with a total of EUR 11.2 billion.
This weekend the governments of Belgium, Luxembourg and the Netherlands held higher-level consultations with the President of the European Central Bank and the European Commission's economic competence officer.
The first eurozone crisis was experienced by Fortis Bank in the context of the international financial crisis that has been taking place in several waves over a year ago.
According to the decision taken early Sunday morning, the three States will buy approximately half (49 percent) of the Bank's property in their area.
The Bank will certainly sell a portion of its business, including in particular the activities - mainly insurance - purchased last year from ABN Amró.
Fortis shares began a sharp decline last week and by the second half of the week there were already signs of a major crisis in the institution.
However, analysts agree that with its 85,000 employees this bank is too big to allow itself to fail.
The company's shares fell 12 percent on Friday alone, the lowest point in 14 years.
Since January, the value of the shares has fallen by more than two thirds.
Looking at current share prices, the total market value of the group's capital is around 14 billion euros, but according to the company's executives this is not real.
The Bank's management attributed the sharp drop in Fortis shares to the uncertainties of the US market in relation to the approval of the US $700 billion package.
On Monday, the shares already showed a slight increase.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed as the bank's new CEO.
The Bank also sought private investors, but so far no one has made a concrete offer.
The Belgian government had previously assured investors that they would not have to worry, they would not lose their money.
Among the Bank's customers so far there has been no panic, they have not invaded the bank offices to withdraw their money.
Fortis has its own branch in Hungary and has also bought leasing companies.
Fox in the henhouse
In the United States, life and health insurance companies often refuse to sign an insurance contract when they see data on drug purchases.
Privacy policy experts fear that the market for personal data will become uncontrollable.
'There are personal data protection programmes which link the use of prescription data in all cases to the approval of the person concerned.
It must be in independent hands, because otherwise, "we'll trust the fox with the chicken coop", says Richard Dick, designer of the medical prescription tracking program.
Insurance companies make the price of insurance and the amount of compensation dependent on the health status of the client and if they think the risk is excessive, they simply don't make the contract.
Before they sent the client to a medical check-up and signed the contract with him knowing the result of the check.
Dick invented a much cheaper procedure ten years ago: with the customer ID number he can easily get the pharmacies list of medicines purchased in the last year and a half and the program itself draws conclusions about the patient's illness and health.
For example, if you systematically take large doses of cholesterol-lowering pills, it indicates that your blood fat level is practically incurably high, so you are immediately placed in a higher risk category.
There are numerous versions of the programme in circulation, some even setting a risk number, so the insurance company besides the administration has little to do, although there are minor difficulties in this regard.
Among the disadvantages of the programme is that some medicines are multi-use, for example certain substances are used both for headache and heat waves and even as antidepressants.
The latter is a major risk-increasing factor for insurance companies whereas the former are not.
Special companies were set up to consult and process this data, which before acquiring the necessary information from pharmacies, ask for the patient's approval.
The authorities already force them to do this, although they have not received a fine for the negligence so far.
Some companies have also recently been working on lab test results and combining them with drug use data to obtain more accurate information about the patient's health status.
More and more companies have access to this data and simultaneously it is increasingly difficult to control its use.
There is a unique law for the protection of personal health data, but it applies only to insurance companies and healthcare providers.
The bill that gives authority to control companies specialized in providing personal data is already before Congress.
Dick Richard acknowledges that this is insufficient: he therefore developed his programme, which will require the specific approval of the person for the provision of his own personal data.
It is another matter that the person cannot deny his approval, because otherwise the insurance companies will not sign the contract with him.
So the hens, after all, are exposed to the fox's good will.
