The European Union doubles its trade with India
As the European Union and India are mutually trade partners, this issue along with other mainly global problems dominated the agenda of the ninth summit.
A Franco-Indian summit will also be held today, mainly on cooperation in nuclear energy.
Although the European Union recognizes that India is a major developing democratic power that should have more voice and voice in international affairs, member countries have not yet been able to reach a common denominator on whether they should support New Delhi as a permanent member of the UN Security Council.
This question has not been addressed at the ninth summit launched yesterday in Marseille.
French President Nicolas Sarkozy, President-in-Office of the EU, Commission President José Manuel Barroso and Javier Solana, the chief foreign policy officer, welcomed Manmohan Singh, Prime Minister of India, with whom they reached an agreement to double their trade over five years, i.e. increase to more than 100 billion euros.
Given that between 2000 and 2007 trade in goods increased from 25 billion to 55 billion, this is not an overly ambitious objective.
The 26 existing bilateral civil aviation agreements with India have thus been legally harmonized, so that air transport can also fly in the future.
India intends to sign the free trade agreement with the Union by the end of 2009.
Sarkozy promised to speed up the negotiations.
The objective is balance, because while the EU is India's leading trading partner, New Delhi is only ninth among the Union's trading partners.
The summit focused on global affairs.
Both sides condemned the situation in Afghanistan and Pakistan and terrorism - all forms of terrorism - and urged the convening of a UN conference.
The conclusion of the Doha trade liberalization round was also pressed, although both sides bear a heavy responsibility for its failure.
The EU has confirmed that it will stick to its energy and climate programme, meaning that it wants to reduce polluting emissions by at least 20 per cent by 2020.
India also agrees with this, as at next year's climate conference a global agreement should be reached and greenhouse gas emissions should be reduced by 50 percent by 2050.
They also wanted to prevent food prices from rising and supported the convening of an international conference to review the financial crisis.
Today the head of government of India will travel to the French capital, where he will - at a bilateral meeting - sign an agreement on the peaceful use of nuclear energy.
Paris is confident that French companies will receive contracts worth 20 billion euros to build nuclear reactors.
According to news agency reports, the deal would be for a period of 15 years.
