Found the plane of Steve Fossett the millionaire disappeared a year ago
The remains of the plane of Steve Fossett, the billionaire who disappeared on September 3, 2007 while flying over the Nevada desert have been found.
The debris has been found on a plateau at an altitude of 3,000 meters in the Mammoth Lakes Nevada mountain range, on the border between California and Nevada.
Inside the plane, there were no human remains.
Madera County Sheriff John Anderson has dispelled the remaining doubts: "The plane has been located, we have sent a squadron, and now we have confirmation that it is the very thing Steve Fossett was flying on the day he disappeared", he said at a press conference.
The sheriff has said no human remains have been found on the plane or in the vicinity.
The 63-year-old millionaire was pronounced dead in February.
The U.S. Transportation Safety Board (TSB) has announced that hours after the remains were spotted, a team of investigators has been dispatched to identify the apparatus: it belongs to the Bellanca 8kcab, dispersed since September 3, 2007, when Fossett took off from Yerington, Nevada, for a three-hour flight.
Yesterday, always in California, not far from the Nevada border, some of Fossett's personal remains have been found by a couple near his Mammoth Lakes home.
These are two documents with Fossett's name on them, both issued by the Illinois Federal Aviation Administration, cash and a sweater.
Fossett's search had been interrupted a month after he disappeared.
The millionaire had won a place in history thanks to a long series of firsts.
In 2002, on his sixth attempt, he had become the first man to complete a world tour in an air balloon: two weeks of solo flight.
Three years later he had made the world tour by plane and without stops.
Among his records, also that of having flown at 15,445 meters above the Andes, but with a co-pilot.
